to calculate the mean, variable sample and logical work, since they are numeric. Varible vec_char and vec_factor dont work, since they are not numeric. when use as. numericto logical, vec_char, and vec_factor, logical and vec_factor are converted to numeric numbers, while vec_char cannot be converted.

#Create a data frame 
library(tidyverse)
#x: a random sample of size 1000 from a standard Normal distribution
example_df = tibble(
x = rnorm(1000, mean = 0, sd = 1),
#y: a random sample of size 1000 from a standard Normal distribution
y = rnorm(1000, mean = 0, sd = 1),
#A logical vector indicating whether the x + y > 0
logical = x + y > 0, 
#A numeric vector created by coercing the above logical vector
numeric_vector = as.numeric(logical), 
#A factor vector created by coercing the above logical vector
factor_vector = as.factor(logical)) 
mean(example_df$x)
## [1] -0.05020753
median(example_df$x)
## [1] -0.07836376

short description using inline R code

The size of dataset is 1000, 5 The mean is -0.0502075 The median is -0.0783638 The proportion of cases for which the logical vector is TRUE is 0.484

#Make a scatterplot of y vs x, and color points using the logical variable 
ggplot(example_df, aes(x = x, y = y, color = logical)) + geom_point()

ggsave("scatter_plot.pdf", height = 4, width = 6)
#numeric variable
ggplot(example_df, aes(x = x, y = y, color = numeric_vector)) + geom_point()

#factor variable
ggplot(example_df, aes(x = x, y = y, color = factor_vector)) + geom_point()

The three color spots look similar, and they are intensive around x=0 and y=0. It seems like the plots all have positive relationship.
